        @{"     " link Surfaces.Maximum_Smoothing_Angle } Maximum Smoothing Angle
        @{"     " link Surfaces.Double_Sided            } Double Sided
        @{"     " link Surfaces.Continue                } Continue

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Current_Surface "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces
@prev Surfaces.Current_Surface

    Surfaces - Current Surface


            This specifies which surface is the current one to be operated
        on or modified using the Surface menu options. The surface shown
        must be loaded into the Layout editor, and will be accessible by
        pressing the gadget. The list of all surfaces currently in memory
        will be provided, from which the current surface may be selected.
        If a desired surface is not listed in the list of available
        surfaces, it must be loaded from disk using the Load Surface
        command.

            @{"     " link Surfaces.Load_Surface            } Surfaces - Load Surface
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L         } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Load_Surface "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Load Surface


            This allows a new surface to be loaded from the disk drive,
        including all of its surface characteristics. The Load Surface
        command uses the standard file requester. The surface will then
        be available and may be selected as the current surface by using
        the Current Surface command.

            @{"     " link Surfaces.Current_Surface         } Surfaces - Current Surface
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L         } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Save_Surface "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Save Surface


            This allows a new surface to be saved to the disk drive,
        including all of its surface characteristics. The Save Surface
        command uses the standard file requester. If a surface is changed
        but is not saved, it will not be stored to disk for future use.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Rename_Surface "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Rename Surface


            This option is used to rename a surface. When loading multiple
        objects with the same name, each individual object is identified
        by an ID number. Surfaces within these objects with common surface
        names will not have unique ID numbers, but will instead share
        characteristics. This allows a surface to share its own individual
        characteristics as compared to other surfaces of the same name.
        The name of the new surface is not recorded on disk unless the
        surface is saved.

                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R} Rename

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Surface_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Surface Color


            This is used to modify the color of a surface of an object.
        This will open the palette requester, allowing the Red, Green,
        and Blue color settings to be altered. The resulting color will
        be displayed in the bottom portion of the screen. A list of
        colors and their RGB values may be found in the Index.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table  } INDEX: Color Table

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Luminosity "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Luminosity


            This specifies the amount that an object glows. The surface
        will glow using an increasing intensity as the luminosity is
        increased.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Diffuse_Level "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Diffuse Level


            This allows an object's surface to diffuse light in various
        directions, making it appear as though it is either brighter or
        darker depending on its position in relation to the light. A
        higher percentage will cause more light to diffuse.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Outline_Only "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Outline Only


            This will render the polygons as an outline only, and will
        leave the internal area unrendered. The outlines will be rendered
        in the colors specified by their surface colors. This rendering
        technique is useful in creating CAD style renderings or mechanical
        presentations.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Additive "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Additive


            This specifies that the color of a surface is to have the
        surface colors of all objects behind it added to it. Since adding
        together various color values will increase the amount of Red,
        Green, and Blue, the colors can be added to a maximum of White,
        which is the most amount of color any given can be visible as.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Sharp_Terminator "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Sharp Terminator


            This causes shadows on objects to have sharp edges as opposed
        to gradiated edges. A gradiated edge would be readily apparant
        on an object that has light aimed towards it from various angles,
        while a sharp edge is created when light rays are near parallel.
        This type of sharp edge occurs when the light source is a large
        distance from the object receiving the shadow.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Specular_Level "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Specular Level


            This specifies the amount of specular highlights that a
        surface may have. This is evident as a small highlight may appear
        to shine across the surface or edges of an object, often as light
        passes across it or as it moves and rotates. The color of the
        specular highlight will match the color of the light cast upon
        it unless Color Highlights are specified.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Color_Highlights "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Color Highlights


            This specifies that specular highlights from the surface of
        an object will combine the color of the light source with the
        color of the surface it is reflected off of. This option can only
        be used if the Specular Level is greater than 0%.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Glossiness "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Glossiness


            Glossiness specifies the amount of space occupied by a
        specular highlight. A surface that has high glossiness will have
        larger highlights, while a surface with low glossiness will have
        smaller highlights. Glossiness may be specified as either Low,
        Medium, High, or Maximum.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Reflectivity "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Reflectivity


            This field specifies the percentage of reflection that the
        surface will have. A reflection level of 0% will cause no
        reflection, while a value of 100% will cause the surface to
        appear as a complete reflection of other surfaces. If a surface
        is set to reflect 100%, the surface color, image maps, and its
        textures may not be shown.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Reflected_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Reflected Image


            This specifies that the surface is to have the specified
        image reflected off of it. This is used to create mirrored
        surfaces. The amount of reflection can be specified using the
        Reflectivity field.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Transparency "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Transparency


            This specifies the amount of transparency of an object. An
        object with 0% transparency will appear solid, while an object
        with 100% transparency will appear invisible.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Color_Filter "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Color Filter


            If the object is somehwat transparent using the Transparency
        setting, this will allow the object to alter the color of any
        light that passes through it. Objects behind the transparent object
        will also appear tinted in the color of the transparent object.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Refractive_Index "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Refractive Index


            The specifies the amount of bending that will occur as a light
        source passes through the surface. Light that passes through air
        generally does not refract, and therefor has a refractive index
        of 1.0. All other transparent surfaces will have a refractive index
        of 1.0 or greater depending on the type of surface. This option is
        only usable when the object has a transparency greater than 0%,
        and the image must be rendered in Realistic mode. When Realistic
        Mode is selected, Trace Refraction must also be specified from the
        same menu in order to allow raytracing of refractive surfaces.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Edge_Transparency "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Edge Transparency


            Specifies the type of edge a surface may have, which may be
        either Opaque, Normal, or Transparent. An Opaque edge creates an
        edge whose threshold of thickness may be modified using the Edge
        Threshold. A Normal edge creates a solid edge about the surface.
        A Transparent edge blends the edge into the ackground images or
        objects based upon the Edge Threshold.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Edge_Threshold "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Edge Threshold


            Specifies the amount of transparency to exist at the edge of
        a surface. This edge may exist over the entire surface of the
        object or it may be limited to the extreme edge, depending on the
        threshold values. This will affect Opaque and Transparent edges
        but not Normal edges. Low thresholds cause sharp gradients, while
        high thresholds cause soft gradients.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Smoothing "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Smoothing


            This option turns on Phong shading. With this option off, all
        edges in an object will be visible as sharp edges. With smoothing
        on, all edges within the threshold that also share common vertices
        will be Phong shaded. This type of shading will cause the edges of
        the adjoining polygons to appear soft and smooth as opposed to
        sharp. In order for smoothing to work properly, the adjacent edges
        must share the same vertices.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Maximum_Smoothing_Angle "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Maximum Smoothing Angle


            This field specifies the threshold in degrees for which Phong
        shading will be performed on two adjoining edges. Any two edges
        that intersect or join at an angle less than this threshold will
        be Phong shaded when the Smoothing option is specified. Any angle
        above this threshold will not be Phong shaded.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Double_Sided "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces

    Surfaces - Double Sided


            This causes the entire surface to become double sided. These
        polygons will have the same surface characteristics, such as color
        or texture maps, applied to each side of the polygon. This is
        used when polygons are meant to be viewed from either side, or to
        assure that some objects have all polygons viewable when imported
        from another program that is based upon double sided polygons.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Surfaces.Continue "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Surfaces
@next Surfaces.Continue

    Surfaces - Continue


            This will close the current window and remember certain
        changes that may have been made to the Layout and its objects
        or images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Layout.Images "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Main
@prev Layout.Surfaces
@next Layout.Lights

    Layout - Images

        @{"     " link Images.Clear_All_Images      } Clear All Images
        @{"     " link Images.Load_Image            } Load Image
        @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence         } Load Sequence
        @{"     " link Images.Current_Image         } Current Image
        @{"     " link Images.Clear_Image           } Clear Image
        @{"     " link Images.Frame_Offset          } Frame Offset
        @{"     " link Images.Loop_Sequence         } Loop Sequence
        @{"     " link Images.Sequence_Loop_Length  } Sequence Loop Length
        @{"     " link Images.Color_Cycling         } Color Cycling
        @{"     " link Images.Low_Cycle_Index       } Low Cycle Index
        @{"     " link Images.High_Cycle_Index      } High Cycle Index
        @{"     " link Images.Continue              } Continue

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Clear_All_Images "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images
@prev Images.Clear_All_Images

    Images - Clear All Images


            This will remove any images in the Layout editor. If you
        require new images to be used in the Layout editor, they must
        be loaded from the hard drive. To load images or sequences of
        images into the Layout editor, you must use the Load Image or
        Load Sequence commands. After selecting this command, the
        current image will be set to (none).

            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image            } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence         } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L     } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Load_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Load Image


            This is used to load an image into the Layout editor, so that
        it may be reflected or wrapped around objects. The loaded image
        will be listed in the table of images, which may be viewed by using
        the cycle gadget for the current image. The Layout can load IFF
        and Framestore images.

            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence         } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L     } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Load_Sequence "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Load Sequence


            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image            } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L     } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Current_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Current Image


            This cycle gadget is used to select the current image which
        may be operated on by the Images menu. Clicking on the cycle
        gadget will open a list of all images loaded into the Layout
        editor. The current image may be selected from this list, and
        its name will appear in the cycle gadget.

            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image            } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence         } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L     } Load

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Clear_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Clear Image


            This is used to delete from memory the current image. If the
        current image is the only image in the Layout editor, there will
        be no current image. A new current image can be selected from
        that cycle gadget if more are loaded into memory. All images may
        be cleared simultaneously using the Clear All Images command.

            @{"     " link Images.Clear_All_Images  } Images - Clear All Images

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Frame_Offset "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Frame Offset


            This is used to specify an offset from the first frame of the
        current animation. The first frame rendered will be the frame
        located at the sum of the First Frame and the Frame Offset. For
        example, if an animation has 100 frames, with the first frame equal
        to 0 and the last frame set to 99, a frame offset of 10 would start
        rendering at frame 10.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Loop_Sequence "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Loop Sequence


            Specifies that the current animation will loop. After
        displaying the last frame of the animation, a looping animation
        will begin animating at the first frame again. The animation will
        loop after the Sequence Loop Length has been reached by the
        current animation frame.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Sequence_Loop_Length "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Sequence Loop Length


            Specifies that a looping animation will begin looping after
        this number of frames has been reached. This is only used if
        the Loop Sequence option is used. For example, in a 100 frame
        animation with the first frame of 1 and the last frame of 100,
        if the Sequence Loop Length is set to 50, then the animation
        will loop between frames 1 and 50, which constitutes 50 frames.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Color_Cycling "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Color Cycling


            This is used to turn on color cycling. This may be set to
        forward or reverse cycling, throught the palette or a range
        within the palette. When cycling is turned on, the colors will
        change to each of the other colors in the palette range specified.
        Colors can only be cycled in images with 1 to 8 bitplanes, not
        including special images such as EHB or HAM.


            If an image has 4 colors, for example Red, Green, Blue, and
        Yellow, the colors will be cycled through each pixel in the same
        order. After the 4th cycle, the process will repeat.

               CYCLE 1         CYCLE 2         CYCLE 3         CYCLE 4

            Color0: Red     Color0: Yellow  Color0: Blue    Color0: Green
            Color1: Green   Color1: Red     Color1: Yellow  Color1: Blue
            Color2: Blue    Color2: Green   Color2: Red     Color2: Yellow
            Color3: Yellow  Color3: Blue    Color3: Green   Color3: Red

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C     } Color Cycling

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Low_Cycle_Index "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - Low Cycle Index


            Specifies the lower color pen to begin color cycling from.
        All colors between the Low Cycle Index and the High Cycle Index
        will be cycled.


            If an image has 4 colors, for example Red, Green, Blue, and
        Yellow, the colors will be cycled through each pixel in the same
        order, within the specified range.  If the Low Cycle Index were
        set to Color1 (the second color pen, preceeded by Color0), then
        all colors from Color1 to Color3 would cycle. After the 3rd cycle,
        the process will repeat. All colors before the Low Cycle Index
        (in this case only Color0) will not be changed.

                       CYCLE 1         CYCLE 2         CYCLE 3

                    Color0: Red     Color0: Red     Color0: Red
                    Color1: Green   Color1: Yellow  Color1: Blue
                    Color2: Blue    Color2: Green   Color2: Yellow
                    Color3: Yellow  Color3: Blue    Color3: Green

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C     } Color Cycling

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.High_Cycle_Index "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images

    Images - High Cycle Index


            Specifies the higher color pen to end color cycling from.
        All colors between the Low Cycle Index and the High Cycle Index
        will be cycled.


            If an image has 4 colors, for example Red, Green, Blue, and
        Yellow, the colors will be cycled through each pixel in the same
        order, within the specified range.  If the High Cycle Index were
        set to Color2 (the third color pen, preceeded by Color0 and Color1),
        then all colors from Color0 to Color2 would cycle. After the 3rd
        cycle, the process will repeat. All colors before the High Cycle
        Index (in this case only Color3) will not be changed.

                       CYCLE 1         CYCLE 2         CYCLE 3

                    Color0: Red     Color0: Blue    Color0: Green
                    Color1: Green   Color1: Red     Color1: Blue
                    Color2: Blue    Color2: Green   Color2: Red
                    Color3: Yellow  Color3: Yellow  Color3: Yellow

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C     } Color Cycling

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Images.Continue "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Images
@next Images.Continue

    Images - Continue


            This will close the current window and remember certain
        changes that may have been made to the Layout and its objects
        or images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Layout.Lights "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Main
@prev Layout.Images
@next Layout.Camera

    Layout - Lights

        @{"     " link Lights.Clear_All_Lights      } Clear All Lights
        @{"     " link Lights.Add_Light             } Add Light
        @{"     " link Lights.Ambient_Color         } Ambient Color
        @{"     " link Lights.Ambient_Intensity     } Ambient Intensity
        @{"     " link Lights.Enable_Lens_Flare     } Enable Lens Flare
        @{"     " link Lights.Enable_Shadow_Maps    } Enable Shadow Maps
        @{"     " link Lights.Current_Light         } Current Light
        @{"     " link Lights.Clear_Light           } Clear Light
        @{"     " link Lights.Rename_Light          } Rename Light
        @{"     " link Lights.Clone_Light           } Clone Light
        @{"     " link Lights.Light_Motion          } Light Motion
        @{"     " link Lights.Light_Color           } Light Color
        @{"     " link Lights.Light_Intensity       } Light Intensity
        @{"     " link Lights.Lens_Flare            } Lens Flare
        @{"     " link Lights.Lens_Flare_Options    } Lens Flare Options
        @{"     " link Lights.Light_Type            } Light Type
        @{"     " link Lights.Intensity_Falloff     } Intensity Falloff
        @{"     " link Lights.Spotlight_Cone_Angle  } Spotlight Cone Angle
        @{"     " link Lights.Spot_Soft_Edge_Angle  } Spot Soft Edge Angle
        @{"     " link Lights.Shadow_Type           } Shadow Type
        @{"     " link Lights.Shadow_Map_Size       } Shadow Map Size
        @{"     " link Lights.Use_Cone_Angle        } Use Cone Angle
        @{"     " link Lights.Shadow_Map_Angle      } Shadow Map Angle
        @{"     " link Lights.Shadow_Fuzziness      } Shadow Fuzziness
        @{"     " link Lights.Continue              } Continue

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Clear_All_Lights "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights
@prev Lights.Clear_All_Lights

    Lights - Clear All Lights


            This option will remove all of the lights from the current
        Layout with the exception of the first light. The specifications
        of the first light is reset to its default settings.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Add_Light "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Add Light


            This option will add a new light to the Layout editor. Each
        new light has the same default settings. Increasing the number
        of lights will increase rendering times, as well as increase the
        intensity of colors rendered when the lights are combined. When
        more than one light is aimed at a given object, it is suggested
        that the intensities of these lights be reduced to avoid
        overexposure on the objects.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Ambient_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Ambient Color


            This option is used to set the amount of ambient light in a
        scene. Ambient light is light that appears on all surfaces in a
        scene, caused by a strong distant light source such as the Sun,
        for which the light is reflected off of other surfaces. For
        example, although our world is naturally lit by the Sun, our
        shadow is cast without removing all light from the objects are
        shadows are cast upon. Ambient light is also used to create
        shades, which is the absence of a direct light source on any
        given surface.
            To adjust the ambient light, sliders may be used to set the
        amount of Red, Green, and Blue color. These values may also be
        entered in the fields that display the current values. These
        values may range from 0 to 255. 0 represents less color and
        255 represents more color.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Ambient_Intensity "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Ambient Intensity


            This specifies the intensity of ambient light. Ambient light
        is the light that is shown on all surfaces of all objects, due
        to strong light sources such as the Sun. If the intensity is too
        high, shadows will not cast well upon objects. If it is too low,
        shadows will blacken out surfaces that they are cast upon.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Enable_Lens_Flare "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Enable Lens Flare


            This is used to specify that all visible light sources will
        create lens flares upon the camera lens. The type of lens flares
        may be defined using the Lens Flare Options.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Enable_Shadow_Maps "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Enable Shadow Maps


            This is used to specify that all visible light rays will cast
        shadows when blocked by objects in the current scene.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Current_Light "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Current Light


            This is used to specify the light which is to be modified
        using the Lights menu in the Layout editor. The current light
        may be selected by clicking on the cycle gadget. A list of all
        available light sources will be listed in a window, and the
        new current light may be selected. If no lights are available
        in the Layout editor, (none) will be listed as the current light.
        A light may be added using the Add Light command.

            @{"     " link Lights.Add_Light             } Lights - Add Light

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Clear_Light "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Clear Light


            This is used to remove the current light from the Layout
        editor. This light will not be available in the list of light
        sources. If the last light source is deleted, the current light
        source will be listed as (none). To add a new light, use the
        Add Light command.

            @{"     " link Lights.Add_Light             } Lights - Add Light

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Rename_Light "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Rename Light


            This command renames the current light source. The new name
        will be used in all references to that light source.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R} Rename

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Clone_Light "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Clone Light


            This command is used to make duplicate copies of the current
        light source. All specifications of the current light will be
        copied, and a new ID number will be assigned to the newly added
        light sources. A requester will open allowing any number of clone
        lights to be created from a given light. All new lights will be
        selectable as the Current Light by using the Current Light command.
        Since ID numbers are generated for clone lights, each clone light
        can be renamed using the Rename Light command.

            @{"     " link Lights.Add_Light         } Lights - Add Light
            @{"     " link Lights.Current_Light     } Lights - Current Light
            @{"     " link Lights.Rename_Light      } Lights - Rename Light

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Light_Motion "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Light Motion


            This is used to specif the type of motion the current light
        will take as time advances each frame. The standard Motion
        Control Panel is used.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Light_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Light Color


            This is used to specify the color of the current light source.
        All lights are defined by three values, based upon a combination
        of Red, Green, and Blue light waves, commonly known as RGB. A
        list of colors and their corresponding RGB values can be found
        in the Index.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Light_Intensity "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Light Intensity


            This is used to specify the intensity level of the current
        light source. The value is a percentage, where 100% is fully
        intense and 0% contains no intensity.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Lens_Flare "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Lens Flare


            This specifies that the current light source will have its
        image reflected off of the lens of the camera. The lens flare
        may have various chatacteristics defined using the Lens Flare
        Options.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Lens_Flare_Options "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Lens Flare Options


            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Light_Type "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Light Type


@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Intensity_Falloff "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Intensity Falloff


            This specifies the amount of intensity that is decreased as
        the light is emmitted from the light source. The light intensity
        decreases by this percentage for every unit distance the light
        travels.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Spotlight_Cone_Angle "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Spotlight Cone Angle


            This is used to specify the angle of the cone for a spotlight.
        The Layout editor will show the shape of the cone specified when
        cone drawing is active. The angle is measured with vertices at
        the light source, a point along the light beam perpendicular to
        the light source, and a point along the circumference of the cone
        perpendiculat to the center point.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Spot_Soft_Edge_Angle "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Spot Soft Edge Angle


            This is used to specify the amount of soft edge to be rendered
        at the edge of a spotlight. To produce a sharp edge, a value of
        0 degrees is specified.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Shadow_Type "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Shadow Type


            Specifies the type of shadow to be rendered by the current
        light source. Shadows may be turned off, ray traced, or shadow
        mapped. Ray tracing will render sharp shadows, while shadow
        mapping may generate soft shadows.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Shadow_Map_Size "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Shadow Map Size


            This is used to specify the amount of memory to be reserved
        when generating shadow maps. Larger amounts of memory will creater
        higher quality shadows, while smaller amounts of memory will
        create shadows of lower quality.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Use_Cone_Angle "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Use Cone Angle


            This is used to specify that all objects in the cone produced
        by a light source will be shadow mapped, when shadow mapping is
        used.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Shadow_Map_Angle "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Shadow Map Angle


            This is used to specify the angle within the cone that will
        have shadow mapping rendered in it when shadow mapping is used.
        This allows particular objects to be rendered with shadow mapping
        which fall within the cone, saving memory and time, as opposed to
        rendering all objects in the cone with shadow maps. If desired,
        all objects in the light's cone may be rendered using the Use
        Cone Angle option.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Shadow_Fuzziness "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights

    Lights - Shadow Fuzziness


            This is used to specify the softness of the edges of the
        shadow created by objects within the current light. Lower
        values create sharper edges, while higher values create softer
        edges.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Lights.Continue "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Lights
@next Lights.Continue

    Lights - Continue


            This will close the current window and remember certain
        changes that may have been made to the Layout and its objects
        or images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Layout.Camera "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Main
@prev Layout.Lights
@next Layout.Effects

    Layout - Camera

        @{"     " link Camera.Camera_Motion         } Camera Motion
        @{"     " link Camera.Zoom_Factor           } Zoom Factor
        @{"     " link Camera.Rendering_Type        } Rendering Type
        @{"     " link Camera.Trace_Shadows         } Trace Shadows
        @{"     " link Camera.Trace_Reflection      } Trace Reflection
        @{"     " link Camera.Trace_Refraction      } Trace Refraction
        @{"     " link Camera.Resolution            } Resolution
        @{"     " link Camera.Overscan              } Overscan
        @{"     " link Camera.Letterbox             } Letterbox
        @{"     " link Camera.Pixel_Aspect_Ratio    } Pixel Aspect Ratio
        @{"     " link Camera.Use_Fewer_Segments    } Use Fewer Segments
        @{"     " link Camera.Limited_Region        } Limited Region
        @{"     " link Camera.Antialiasing          } Antialiasing
        @{"     " link Camera.Soft_Filter           } Soft Filter
        @{"     " link Camera.Adaptive_Sampling     } Adaptive Sampling
        @{"     " link Camera.Sampling_Threshold    } Sampling Threshold
        @{"     " link Camera.Field_Rendering       } Field Rendering
        @{"     " link Camera.Motion_Blur           } Motion Blur
        @{"     " link Camera.Depth_of_Field        } Depth of Field
        @{"     " link Camera.Particle_Blur         } Particle Blur
        @{"     " link Camera.Blur_Length           } Blur Length
        @{"     " link Camera.Focal_Distance        } Focal Distance
        @{"     " link Camera.Continue              } Continue

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Camera_Motion "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera
@prev Camera.Camera_Motion

    Camera - Camera Motion


@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Zoom_Factor "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Zoom Factor


            This is used to specify the amount of zooming the camera
        has performed using its lenses. A lower zoom factor will
        produce a wider view angle, will a higher zoom factor will
        produce a thinner view angle.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.C     } @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Camera @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L     } @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Lens   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.Z     } @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Zoom   @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Rendering_Type "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Rendering Type


            This is used to specify the method of rendering to perform
        in the scene. Some rendering methods are meant merely for testing
        animations since they render much quicker than the more complicated
        methods.

            WIREFRAME       Specifies that the images will be rendered in
                            wireframes, showing polygon edges, with no
                            texures or brushmaps shown.

                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Edge        @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.W} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Wireframe   @{FG TEXT}


            QUICKSHADE      Specifies that the images will be rendered
                            with solid polygons, yet without textures,
                            brushmaps, shadows, or transparancies.

                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Polygon     @{FG TEXT}


            REALISTIC       Specifies that the images will be rendered
                            with all available textures, brushmaps,
                            shadows, transparencies, lens flares, ray
                            trace modes, and other special options.

                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Brushmap        @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Lens Flare      @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Ray Trace       @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Shadow          @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.T} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Texture         @{FG TEXT}
                                @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.T} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Transparency    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Trace_Shadows "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Trace Shadows


            Specifies that ray tracing will be used to produce selected
        shadows. Objects must be set on an individual basis whether or
        not they will receive or cast shadows, and lights must be set
        on an individual basis whether or not they will cast shadows.

            @{"     " link Objects.Self_Shadow          } Objects - Self Shadow
            @{"     " link Objects.Cast_Shadow          } Objects - Cast Shadow
            @{"     " link Objects.Receive_Shadow       } Objects - Receive Shadow
            @{"     " link Lights.Enable_Shadow_Maps    } Lights - Enable Shadow Maps
            @{"     " link Lights.Shadow_Type           } Lights - Shadow Type
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.O} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Object  @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Light   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Shadow  @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Trace_Reflection "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Trace Reflection


            Specifies that surfaces capable of reflecting images will
        reflect images based upon their assigned levels of reflection.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Reflection    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Trace_Refraction "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Trace Refraction


            Specifies that surfaces capable of refracting images will
        refract images based upon their assigned levels of refraction.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/refraction   } INDEX: Light Refraction
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.R} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Refraction    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Resolution "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Resolution


@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Overscan "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Overscan


            This is used to specify that overscan areas of the scene
        will be rendered. The overscan area will be visible in the
        Layout editor by a dashed line surrounding the underscan area.
        Overscan images are often used when animations and images are
        to be displayed on television sets.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.O} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Overscan     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.U} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Underscan    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Letterbox "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Letterbox


            This is used to specify that the image will be rendered in
        the cinematic letterbox format. The upper and lower portions of
        the screen will be rendered with a solid black border. The
        letterbox area will be visible in the Layout editor by a dashed
        line surrouning the letterbox viewing area.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Letterbox    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Pixel_Aspect_Ratio "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Pixel Aspect Ratio


            Specifies which aspect ratio should be used by the image
        when rendered. Depending on the monitor or television settings,
        rendered images may appear skewed.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Aspect Ratio    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Use_Fewer_Segments "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Use Fewer Segments


            This specifies that a larger buffer is to be used when
        rendering images. Although it does require more memory, it will
        also increase rendering times since it no longer requires that
        portions of the image be transferred and joined together.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.M} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Memory     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Segment    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Limited_Region "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Limited Region


            Specifies that only a portion of the scene is to be rendered.
        The viewable area in the Layout editor may be resized by dragging
        the borders of the viewing area.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Antialiasing "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Antialiasing


            Specifies that any jagged lines in the rendered image are
        to be antialiased. This will cause the jagged lines to become
        smoother as each pass is made over the image. Higher levels of
        anitialiasing will cause jagged edges to become smoother, while
        lower levels will cause them to be less smooth.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Antialiasing    @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Edge            @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Soft_Filter "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Soft Filter


            This is used to specify that edges are to be softer, as opposed
        to sharp, when rendered.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Edge          @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Soft Edge     @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.S} @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Sharp Edge    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Adaptive_Sampling "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Adaptive Sampling


            This is used to specify that antialiasing will be based on
        a threshold of values to determine whether or not an edge will
        be antialiased.

            @{"     " link Camera.Sampling_Threshold              } Camera - Sampling Threshold
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Adaptive Sampling   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Antialiasing        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Edge                @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Sampling_Threshold "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Sampling Threshold


            This is used to specify the threshold level to determine
        whether or not a give pixel is antialiased when Adaptive Sampling
        is used.

            @{"     " link Camera.Adaptive_Sampling               } Camera - Adaptive Sampling
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Adaptive Sampling   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Antialiasing        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.E}@{FG HIGHLIGHT} Edge                @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Field_Rendering "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Field Rendering


            This specifies that each frame is to be rendered as an
        individual field. This is used to provide smoother animations
        for objects that are moving across the screen. Each frame will
        be rendered as two seperate fields, as opposed to each frame
        being rendered with two fields together.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Animation  @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Field      @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Frame      @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Motion_Blur "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Motion Blur


            This is used to specify that objects moving across the screen
        will appear blurred. This simulates the natural occuring inability
        of the eye or cameras to view sharp edges on fast moving objects.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Blur           @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.M} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Motion Blur    @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Depth_of_Field "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Depth of Field


            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Blur           @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.D} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Depth of Field @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Particle_Blur "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Particle Blur

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Blur           @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.P} @{FG HIGHLIGHT }Particle Blur  @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Blur_Length "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Blur Length

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes                         } Layout - Envelope Editor
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT  } Blur           @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Focal_Distance "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera

    Camera - Focal Distance

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Camera.Continue "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Camera
@next Camera.Continue

    Camera - Continue


            This will close the current window and remember certain
        changes that may have been made to the Layout and its objects
        or images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Layout.Effects "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Main
@prev Layout.Camera
@next Layout.Record

    Layout - Effects

        @{"     " link Effects.Background_Image         } Background Image
        @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Foreground Image
        @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Alpha_Image   } Foreground Alpha Image
        @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Dissolve      } Foreground Dissolve
        @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Key           } Foreground Key
        @{"     " link Effects.Low_Clip_Color           } Low Clip Color
        @{"     " link Effects.High_Clip_Color          } High Clip Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Solid_Backdrop           } Solid Backdrop
        @{"     " link Effects.Zenith_Color             } Zenith Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Sky_Color                } Sky Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Ground_Color             } Ground Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Nadir_Color              } Nadir Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Fog_Type                 } Fog Type
        @{"     " link Effects.Minimum_Fog_Distance     } Minimum Fog Distance
        @{"     " link Effects.Maximum_Fog_Distance     } Maximum Fog Distance
        @{"     " link Effects.Backdrop_Fog             } Backdrop Fog
        @{"     " link Effects.Fog_Color                } Fog Color
        @{"     " link Effects.Dither_Intensity         } Dither Intensity
        @{"     " link Effects.Animated_Dither          } Animated Dither
        @{"     " link Effects.Color_Saturation         } Color Saturation
        @{"     " link Effects.Continue                 } Continue

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Background_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects
@prev Effects.Background_Image

    Effects - Background Image


            This is used to specify the image to be displayed in the
        background of the scene. All objects will be rendered in front
        of the background image. If the image is smaller than 752x480
        pixels, then it will be centered in the rendered scene. If the
        camera is moved, the background image will remain aligned with
        the camera. The image must be loaded into the Layout editor in
        order to be available for use. This image may be viewed in the
        Layout editor if desired.

            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Alpha_Image   } Effects - Foreground Alpha Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image                } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence             } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.B }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Background   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.I }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Image        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Load         @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Foreground_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Foreground Image


            This is used to specify the image to be displayed in the
        foreground of the scene. All objects will be renderd in back of
        the foreground image. If the image is smaller than 752x480 pixels,
        then it will be centered in the rendered scene. If the camera is
        moved, the foreground image will remain aligned with the camera.
        The image must be loaded into the Layout editor in order to be
        available for use.

            @{"     " link Effects.Background_Image         } Effects - Background Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Alpha_Image   } Effects - Foreground Alpha Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image                } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence             } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Foreground   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.I }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Image        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Load         @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Foreground_Alpha_Image "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Foreground Alpha Image


            This is used to specify the image to be used as an alpha
        channel for composting images. The foreground alpha image is
        a greyscale image with whiter areas showing the foreground image
        and darker areas showing the background image. If the image is
        smaller than 752x480 pixels, then it will be centered in the
        rendered scene. If the camera is moved, the foreground alpha
        image will remain aligned with the camera. The alpha image must
        be loaded into the Layout editor in order to be available for
        use.

            @{"     " link Effects.Background_Image         } Effects - Background Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Image                } Images - Load Image
            @{"     " link Images.Load_Sequence             } Images - Load Sequence
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.A }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Alpha Channel@{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Foreground   @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.I }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Image        @{FG TEXT}
            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.L }@{FG HIGHLIGHT } Load         @{FG TEXT}

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Foreground_Dissolve "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Foreground Dissolve


            This is used to specify the transparency level of the
        foreground image. If the dissolve level is 0%, it is fully
        visible, while a value approaching 100% becomes transparent.

            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes                 } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Foreground_Key "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Foreground Key


            This is used to create transparent color keys in the
        foreground image. All colors within the Low Clip Color and
        High Clip Color range will be fully transparent.

            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Low_Clip_Color           } Effects - Low Clip Color
            @{"     " link Effects.High_Clip_Color          } Effects - High Clip Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Low_Clip_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Low Clip Color


            This is used to set the lower color register to be used
        in creating a transparent range in the foreground image. This
        is toggled on using the Foreground Key command.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Key           } Effects - Foreground Key
            @{"     " link Effects.High_Clip_Color          } Effects - High Clip Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.High_Clip_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - High Clip Color


            This is used to set the higher color register to be used
        in creating a transparent range in the foreground image. This
        is toggled on using the Foreground Key command.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Image         } Effects - Foreground Image
            @{"     " link Effects.Foreground_Key           } Effects - Foreground Key
            @{"     " link Effects.Low_Clip_Color           } Effects - Low Clip Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Solid_Backdrop "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Solid Backdrop


            This is used to specify that the background image will be
        a solid color with no gradients.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Zenith_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Zenith Color


            This is used to specify the color of the sky directly
        above the camera. As the sky is rendered, it will gradually
        change color as it approaches the horizon, depending on what
        the Sky Color is set to.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Sky_Color                } Effects - Sky Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Sky_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Sky Color


            This is used to specify the color of the sky. Since the real
        sky changes color as it is viewed from the horizon to the zenith,
        this color is gradiated between the Sky Color and the Zenith Color.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Zenith_Color             } Effects - Zenith Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Ground_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Ground Color


            This is used to specify the color of the ground plane. Since
        thecolor of the ground gradually changes as it approaches the
        horizon, this color is gradiated with the Nadir Color as it
        approaches the camera.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Nadir_Color              } Effects - Nadir Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Nadir_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Nadir Color


            This is used to specify the color of the ground beneath
        the camera. Since the color of the ground gradually changes as
        it approaches the horizon, this color is gradiated with the
        Ground Color as it approaches the horizon.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table           } INDEX: Color Table
            @{"     " link Effects.Ground_Color             } Effects - Ground Color

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Fog_Type "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Fog Type


            This is used to select the type of fog to be rendered, if
        any. Fog is a rendering effect which causes a gas or cloud to
        appear in a rendered image. Fog may be linear or nonlinear, if
        desired. When fog is turned on, the entire scene in the Layout
        editor is treated as though it is within a fog.

            OFF         Specifies that there is no fog in the current scene.

            LINEAR      Specifies that the current scene has linear fog.

            NONLINEAR   Specifies that the current scene has nonlinear fog.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Minimum_Fog_Distance "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Minimum Fog Distance


            This field specifies the distance for which fog begins to
        affect the visibility of objects. At this minimum distance, the
        fog will be visible in the scene, and any objects in the fog will
        be only partially visible depending on the distance from the
        minimum and the maximum distance of the fog.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Maximum_Fog_Distance "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Maximum Fog Distance


            This field specifies the distance for which fog totally covers
        all objects in the scene that are beyond that point. Any objects
        behind the fog's maximum distance will not be visible, any objects
        in the fog will be partially visible, and any objects in front of
        the fog will not be affected by the fog.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Backdrop_Fog "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Backdrop Fog


            This option is used to specify that the background image is
        to be used to form the fog color of any image that appears upon
        the backdrop. This allows fog to be created in a range of colors,
        and the objects rendered will reflect these color variations.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Fog_Color "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Fog Color


            This field is used to specify the color of the fog in the
        rendered image. A palette requester will open, allowing values
        to be entered manually or by using RGB sliders.

            @{"     " link AORM.Index/Color_Table       } INDEX: Color Table

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Dither_Intensity "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Dither Intensity


            This specifies the intensity of the dithering pattern used on
        a surface. This may be set to OFF, NORMAL, 2x, and 4x. Higher
        intensities will cause a surface to be rendered with more gradient
        pixels between two solid colors.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Animated_Dither "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Animated Dither


            This option specifies that any dithering patterns will not
        be consistant from frame to frame, and will instead use a different
        seed value in generating the dithering. This option should not be
        used if a surface is intended to remain constant from frame to
        frame.

            @{"     " link AORM.Glossary/Glossary.F     } Frame

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Color_Saturation "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects

    Effects - Color Saturation


            This field specifies the amount of color saturation. This may
        be set at 100% for an image with maximum color, or it may be set
        to 0% for an image with no color, rendered in black and white.

            @{"     " link Layout.Envelopes             } Layout - Envelope Editor

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node Effects.Continue "Lightwave 3D - Layout"
@toc Layout.Effects
@next Effects.Continue

    Effects - Continue


            This will close the current window and remember certain
        changes that may have been made to the Layout and its objects
        or images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


